@baseUrl = http://localhost:8080

# =============================================================================
# Circuit Breaker Verification Scenario
#
# Prerequisites
#   - scenario.http STEP 1-4 has been run at least once so that
#     customerToken, ownerToken, storeId, product1Id globals exist.
#     (OR run PHASE 0 sign-in steps below, then set storeId / product1Id manually.)
#   - All four backend services and docker-compose DBs are running.
#
# CB config (notification instance)
#   sliding-window-size:              10 calls
#   minimum-number-of-calls:           5
#   failure-rate-threshold:           50 %  (5/5 failures = 100 % → opens immediately)
#   slow-call-duration-threshold:      3 s
#   wait-duration-in-open-state:      30 s
#   permitted-calls-in-half-open:      3
#
# Phases
#   PHASE 0  Setup        — refresh tokens, prepare a cart for checkout tests
#   PHASE 1  CLOSED       — notification-service UP, real responses
#   PHASE 2  Trip the CB  — stop notification-service, run [2-1]…[2-5] in sequence
#                           each call blocks ~3 s then fails; circuit opens after [2-5]
#   PHASE 3  OPEN         — instant fallbacks, no network calls to notification-service
#   PHASE 4  Recovery     — restart notification-service, circuit closes after 3 probes
# =============================================================================


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 0 — Setup
# =============================================================================

### [0-1] Sign in — CUSTOMER  →  saves customerToken
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/users/signin
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "mentee@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

> {%
client.global.set("customerToken", "Bearer " + response.body.accessToken);
%}

###

### [0-2] Sign in — OWNER  →  saves ownerToken
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/users/signin
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "mentor@example.com",
  "password": "password123"
}

> {%
client.global.set("ownerToken", "Bearer " + response.body.accessToken);
%}

###

### [0-3] Add product to cart  →  saves cbCartId1 (used in PHASE 1 checkout)
# Uses storeId and product1Id saved by scenario.http
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId1", response.body.id);
%}

###

### [0-4] Add product to cart  →  saves cbCartId2 (used in PHASE 3 checkout)
# Previous cart is now active — will be reused if not yet checked out.
# Run this AFTER PHASE 1 checkout so a new cart is created here.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId2", response.body.id);
%}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 1 — CB CLOSED  (notification-service must be UP)
#
# Expected: all calls reach notification-service; real 200 responses.
# =============================================================================

### [1-1] List notifications — real response (200, [] if no data yet)
# CB state: CLOSED
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [1-2] Mark all read — real response (200)
# CB state: CLOSED
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/read-all
Authorization: {{customerToken}}

###

### [1-3] Checkout — 200; createNotification fires async and succeeds
# CB state: CLOSED — notification is actually sent
# Check notification-service logs: POST /internal/notifications 201
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId1}}
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 2 — Trip the circuit
#
# ACTION: Stop notification-service now (Ctrl+C in its terminal).
#
# Run [2-1] through [2-5] one by one.
# Each call will block for ~3 s (read timeout), then return 200 via fallback.
# The circuit breaker records each as a SLOW call (≥ 3 s threshold) or error.
# After [2-5]: 5 calls recorded, 100 % failure/slow rate ≥ 50 % threshold → OPEN.
#
# Watch BFF logs for:
#   [CB] listMyNotifications fallback: ...
# =============================================================================

### [2-1] List — slow/failure 1 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-2] List — slow/failure 2 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-3] List — slow/failure 3 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-4] List — slow/failure 4 of 5  (~3 s wait)
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [2-5] List — slow/failure 5 of 5  (~3 s wait)  →  circuit opens after this
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 3 — CB OPEN  (notification-service still DOWN)
#
# All calls return instantly — no network attempt to notification-service.
# BFF logs show [CB] fallback messages.
# =============================================================================

### [3-1] List — instant 200 []  (fallback, no timeout wait)
# CB state: OPEN
# Expected response: []
# BFF log: [CB] listMyNotifications fallback: CircuitBreaker 'notification' is OPEN ...
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [3-2] Mark all read — instant 200  (fallback)
# CB state: OPEN
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/read-all
Authorization: {{customerToken}}

###

### [3-3] Checkout — instant 200, no 3 s wait for notification
# CB state: OPEN — createNotification fast-fails via CallNotPermittedException
# Order is created normally; only the async notification is skipped
# BFF log: [CB] createNotification skipped (CallNotPermittedException): ...
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId2}}
}

###


# =============================================================================
# PHASE 4 — Recovery
#
# ACTION: Wait 30 s (automatic OPEN → HALF_OPEN transition).
# ACTION: Restart notification-service.
#
# The next 3 calls are probes in HALF_OPEN state.
# All 3 succeed → circuit closes (CLOSED).
# =============================================================================

### [4-1] List — probe 1 of 3 (HALF_OPEN → if success, counts toward closing)
# Expected: real response from notification-service (200, [])
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-2] List — probe 2 of 3
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-3] List — probe 3 of 3  →  circuit closes after this
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/notifications/list
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "unreadOnly": false
}

###

### [4-4] Confirm CB CLOSED — checkout creates order AND sends notification
# BFF log: no [CB] fallback message → real notification delivered
# notification-service log: POST /internal/notifications 201
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/carts
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "productId": {{product1Id}},
  "storeId": {{storeId}},
  "quantity": 1
}

> {%
client.global.set("cbCartId3", response.body.id);
%}

###

PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/carts/checkout
Authorization: {{customerToken}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "cartId": {{cbCartId3}}
}

###
